{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516446"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:43:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:43:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12627"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12627"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.03,0.58,0.3,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5112"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"35506"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5112","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5112"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12627"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"20376"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1873"},{"type":"tags","id":"1875"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2664"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8568"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8887"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"35506","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/35506"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 59-year-old female presents with fatigue, shortness of breath, and swelling in both her legs. Her past medical history includes rheumatic heart disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her blood pressure is 130/85 mmHg, and pulse is regular with a rate of 80/min. She has a raised JVP. Palpation demonstrates a right ventricular heave, with the apex beat palpable in the 5th intercostal space, midclavicular line. Auscultation demonstrates S1 and S2, with an added pansystolic murmur heard best at the left lower sternal border, which increases on inspiration.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mitral valve prolapse","Aortic stenosis","Tricuspid regurgitation","Mitral regurgitation","Pulmonary stenosis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBased on the patient\u0027s history and examination findings,\u003Cstrong\u003E tricuspid regurgitation\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis. The raised JVP and peripheral oedema suggest right-sided heart failure, which is commonly caused by tricuspid regurgitation. A pansystolic murmur heard best at the left lower sternal border which gets louder on inspiration also support the diagnosis. The presence of a right ventricular heave further supports this. Her history of rheumatic heart disease may be the underlying aetiology. Other causes of \u003Cstrong\u003Etricuspid regurgitation\u003C/strong\u003E include infective endocarditis, carcinoid syndrome, Ebstein anomaly, and connective-tissue diseases etc.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMitral valve prolapse\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as click-murmur syndrome, is the bulging of one or both of the mitral valve flaps into the left atrium during the contraction of the heart. It can cause a variety of symptoms, including fatigue and shortness of breath, but typically does not cause swelling in the legs or a raised JVP. The murmur associated with mitral valve prolapse is usually a mid-systolic click whose intensity increases on expiration and with the handgrip manoeuvre.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAortic stenosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a narrowing of the aortic valve, which controls blood flow from the left ventricle to the aorta. The murmur associated with aortic stenosis is usually a systolic ejection murmur heard best at the right upper sternal border and radiating to the carotids which increases in intensity on expiration and becomes softer with the handgrip manoeuvre and Valsalva manoeuvre. It is most commonly caused by age-related or congenital calcification followed by rheumatic fever, systemic lupus erythematosus, Paget\u0027s disease etc.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMitral regurgitation\u003C/strong\u003E can present with pulmonary oedema, indicating left-sided heart failure. The characteristic murmur associated with this condition is a pansystolic murmur heard best at the apex of the heart and radiating to the axilla which becomes louder on expiration with the handgrip manoeuvre. The Valsalva manoeuvre decreases its intensity. Common aetiolgical factors include rheumatic fever, myocardial infarction, connective tissue disorders, cardiomyopathies, myxoma etc.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary stenosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a narrowing of the pulmonary valve, which controls blood flow from the right ventricle to the pulmonary artery usually congenital in origin. It typically causes a systolic ejection murmur.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A pansystolic murmur heard best at the left lower sternal border, with a raised JVP and peripheral oedema suggest tricuspid regurgitation.","Tricuspid regurgitation increases with inspiration"],"references":["Shah PM, Raney AA. Tricuspid valve disease. Curr Probl Cardiol. 2008 Feb. 33(2):47-84."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"20376"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12627"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"20376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/20376"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-05-03T09:04:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2023-05-03T09:04:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"dat